post0.title: Primitives Hacks
post0.content: // lower case is primitive, upper case is wrapper class public class FinalGradeCalculator { public static void main(String[] args) { int anInt = 100; double aDouble = 89.9; boolean aBoolean = true; // wrapper classes are more like OBJECTS; you can run methods on a wrapper class (ie. length of string) // everything in java is object; obejcts have functionality like getters, setters, methods, etc // not primitives but essential; capital data types are not primitive String aString = "Hello, World!"; // wrapper class shortcut assignment String aStringFormal = new String("Greetings, World!"); System.out.println("anInt: " + anInt); System.out.println("aDouble: " + aDouble); System.out.println("aBoolean: " + aBoolean); System.out.println("aString: " + aString); System.out.println("aStringFormal: " + aStringFormal); } } DefinePrimitives.main(null) . anInt: 100 aDouble: 89.9 aBoolean: true aString: Hello, World! aStringFormal: Greetings, World! .

page3.title: Notes
page3.content: Notes . Primitives Lesson . . Primitives: Basic data types, don’t store any information beyond the data itself (ie. int, char, float, double) | Wrapper Classes: More complex, similar to objects. Can run methods on wrapper classes (ie. String) | .
